@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(xvii) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it uses a RANGE (`1..n`). eval evaluates a range to a list of the
-- integers in `[from, to)` (exclusive) — `1..5` → `[1, 2, 3, 4]`; the compute spine has
-- no range lowering — `normComp`/`norm` reach the `Range` AST node and refuse it (the
-- `default` arm of `normComp`). The differential harness must report it `unsupported` — a
-- CLEAN refusal at the compiler frontier, never a miscompile.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references; D1(ix) PAST first-class BUILTIN references;
-- D1(x) PAST short-circuit `&&`/`||`; D1(xi) PAST non-tail `if` as a value; D1(xii) PAST
-- non-tail `match` as a value; D1(xiii) PAST multi-clause `def`s; D1(xiv) PAST reassignment;
-- D1(xv) PAST atom literals; D1(xvi) PAST duration literals; D1(xvii) PAST `for`
-- COMPREHENSIONS (nested generators × filters → a list; see compile_comprehension_test).
-- The frontier now sits at RANGES. This file uses one, so it still refuses; when ranges
-- lower (a later D1 slice, an integer-fill list builder), it flips from `unsupported` to a
-- print with no edit.

def upto(n: Number): List(Number)
  for (x in 1..n) -> x

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  println(upto(5))
